               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-202-person1799">
                  THOMAS 
                  RANCE
               <interp inst="t18300415-202-person1799" type="surname" value="RANCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-202-person1799" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-202-person1799" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to Mr. Martin Ware, of Bloomsbury-square. On the afternoon of the 2nd of April, I was out with my master's carriage in the <placeName id="t18300415-202-crimeloc1128">King's-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-202-crimeloc1128" type="placeName" value="King's-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-202-crimeloc1128" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-202-off1125 t18300415-202-crimeloc1128"></join> - I went to knock at a door, and saw the prisoner in an area; our coachman saw him, and said, "What are you at there?" he said, "It is only my cap;" two more boys were standing there - the prisoner had got the window up; he came over the rails - the coachman said to me,"You go after him;" which I did, and a porter stopped him - I took off his cap, and found five spoons in it.</p>

               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183004150097"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-202-person1800">
                  ROBERT 
                  KELLEY
               <interp inst="t18300415-202-person1800" type="surname" value="KELLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-202-person1800" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-202-person1800" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a batter. I saw Rance running after the prisoner, and crying Stop thief! the prisoner was very much out of breath; I met him - he began to cry, and desired me not to stop him; I seized him by the tail of his coat - he struggled a little, and tried to get away, but I saw these spoons, and gave him to an officer.</p>
